els of agency and competence not usually assigned to children and teenage minors, and disrupt mainstream notions of what practices are appropriate at their ages. Leaving school and family in Mexico and financially supporting not only themselves through their work in New York City, but also their families back home, these youths are independent teenage migrants who, upon migration, wish to assume or resume autonomy and agency rather than dependence. This book also explores community and family understandings about survival and social mobility in an era of extreme global economic inequality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aForeign workerszMexico. 0aForeign workerszUnited States. 0aTeenage immigrantszMexico. 0aTeenage immigrantszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aimmigrant, mexican immigrant, central america, homeland, migrant, teenage migrant, teenage immigrant, NYC, new york city, poverty, NAFTA, north american free trade agreement, free trade agreement, mexican teen, social mobility, economic inequality, inequality.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Economics, Law & Social Sciences 2019 ENGz978311061013008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2019z9783110606485oZDB-23-DSW40uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/9780813589831zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813589831423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813589831.jpg  a978-3-11-061013-0  EBOOK PACKAGE Economics, Law & Social Sciences 2019 ENGb2019  a978-3-11-061076-5  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishb2019